Source: ubuntu-game-session
Section: misc
Priority: optional
Maintainer: Ken VanDine <ken.vandine@canonical.com>
Build-Depends: debhelper-compat (= 13),
              build-essential
Standards-Version: 4.6.2

Package: ubuntu-game-session
Architecture: all
Depends: gamescope,
        sxhkd,
        gdm3,
        snapd,
        ${misc:Depends}
Description: Ubuntu Game Session (Steam OS-like gaming experience)
 Installs a Gamescope-based Steam Gamepad UI as an optional Wayland session.
 Users can select "Ubuntu Game Session" from the GDM login screen to launch
 the full-screen Steam interface — a Steam OS-like experience on Ubuntu.
 .
 Suitable for desktops and laptops as an optional manually-selected session.
 Install ubuntu-game-handheld for the full handheld console-mode experience
 with automatic boot into gaming mode.

Package: ubuntu-game-launcher
Architecture: all
Depends: ubuntu-game-session,
         gamemode,
         mangohud,
         ${misc:Depends}
Replaces: ubuntu-game-desktop
Conflicts: ubuntu-game-desktop
Description: Gaming launchers and helpers for the GNOME desktop
 Adds gaming enhancements to the regular Ubuntu GNOME desktop instead of
 shipping a separate compositor or session. Use GNOME for everything (Settings,
 network, audio, power, the app grid) and reach for gamescope only where it
 helps.
 .
 Provides:
  - GameMode (always-on CPU/GPU tuning while a game runs — a near-free win)
  - MangoHud (opt-in FPS / frametime / temperature overlay)
  - ubuntu-game-run: a composable wrapper that adds GameMode, and optionally
    MangoHud and nested gamescope, around any command. Use it as a Steam
    per-game launch-option prefix: "ubuntu-game-run -- %command%"
  - a "Steam (Gamescope)" application entry that launches the whole Steam
    client inside nested gamescope so every game inherits FSR upscaling,
    frame pacing, and the MangoHud overlay
 .
 For the maximum-framerate console experience (gamescope owning the display
 with no desktop compositor underneath) use the ubuntu-game-session kiosk,
 which this package depends on and which also installs the Steam snap.

Package: ubuntu-game-handheld
Architecture: all
Depends: ubuntu-game-session,
        hhd,
        acpi-call-dkms,
        ${misc:Depends}
Description: Ubuntu Game Session autologin for handheld gaming PCs
 Configures GDM to automatically log in to Ubuntu Game Session on every boot,
 suitable for handheld gaming PCs (Lenovo Legion Go, Steam Deck, and similar).
 .
 Installs and configures:
  - GDM autologin into Ubuntu Game Session on every boot
  - Handheld Daemon (HHD) for TDP and controller management
  - HHD overlay for in-game quick access
  - Seamless switching between Ubuntu Game Session and Ubuntu desktop
  - Virtual keyboard for touchscreen / handheld input
 .
 Depends on ubuntu-game-session and hhd. Remove the package to fully revert
 to original Ubuntu behaviour.
